hotel.title: Rome Rome country house 30min from Rome city centre, with swimming pool & horses
hotel.description: Less than 30 minutes from the centre of Rome, along the ancient Via Salaria, the 'Fonte di Papa” country guest house is located inside the Marcigliana Nature Reserve. Its origins start at the end of the 1800's and is part of an old property, where main agricultural activities were wine production in the “Fonte di Papa” cellars and horse breeding. Today, this country guest house is one of the few agricultural properties left in Rome that still maintains its original and natural predisposition for raising horses and experiencing farming life. The property consists of 10 hectares of flat land and 2 old farmhouses.

compound_document.title: Patio Ponds | Patio Design With Water Feature

text_clipping.text: Most people think of patio ponds being located in a separate area of the backyard landscape. However, another location for a pond is right at the patio...and built into it. In this design (below), you can see that the pond was located along a lower patio. Due to the grades, it made sense and was more dramatic to have two waterfalls , rather than one. Imagine sitting there and enjoying the sound of the running water and looking at it cascading over the rocks.

The patio is actually two levels which was a nice way to design since the property slopes from the house towards the rear property. The upper level is a combination of a rectangular space and a round patio area. The first part is for lounges or other seating while the round area was meant for a round table and chairs as the outdoor dining furniture.

In both images you will see that lots of plants are added to soften the pond. A landscape tree is always inviting as are evergreen and deciduous (lose their leaves in the winter) shrubs and perennials. Ornamental grasses look great near water and I always like to add other flowers for all season color. See:

Beyond the table and chairs are circular landscape steps that take you down to the lower patio. There are three steps with 6 inch risers. The depth of the treads are 12 inches. (3) 6" risers means that there is an 18" change in elevation...the upper patio is 18" higher than the lower one.

compound_document.title: Garden Design for Organic Vegetable Gardens

image_clipping.caption: Make sure your vegetables are placed in compatible groups. Some ,like peas, lettuce, spinach and radish come in early. Their growing season is short making it possible to plant another variety later. Squash, melons and potatoes are late bloomers and require a long growing season.
